Here's what needs to change for each item when targeting .NET 10:

---

**1. `WebHostBuilder` → `WebApplication.CreateBuilder()`**

The legacy `WebHost.CreateDefaultBuilder()` / `IWebHostBuilder` hosting model is removed. Migrate to the minimal hosting model:

```csharp
// Before (.NET 9)
var host = WebHost.CreateDefaultBuilder(args)
    .UseStartup<Startup>()
    .Build();
host.Run();

// After (.NET 10)
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
// Move Startup.ConfigureServices() inline
var app = builder.Build();
// Move Startup.Configure() inline
app.Run();
```

---

**2. `.WithOpenApi()` removed**

The `WithOpenApi()` extension on minimal API endpoints is removed. Use the built-in OpenAPI document generation instead:

```csharp
// Before (.NET 9)
app.MapGet("/items", () => ...).WithOpenApi();

// After (.NET 10)
builder.Services.AddOpenApi();
// ...
app.MapOpenApi();  // serves the doc at /openapi/v1.json
// Endpoint metadata via attributes/extensions:
app.MapGet("/items", () => ...).WithSummary("Gets items").WithDescription("...");
```

---

**3. `<IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers>` removed**

This MSBuild property (which pulled in `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Api.Analyzers`) is no longer shipped. Remove it from your `.csproj`. The built-in OpenAPI infrastructure and the `[ProducesResponseType]` attributes still work; the dedicated analyzer package is gone.

```xml
<!-- Remove this line -->
<IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers>true</IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers>
```

---

**4. `Microsoft.Extensions.ApiDescription.Client` (NSwag code gen)**

The server-side counterpart (`Microsoft.Extensions.ApiDescription.Server`) now uses the built-in OpenAPI document generator instead of dispatching to Swashbuckle at build time. If you're using NSwag via `ApiDescription.Client`:

- Keep the `ApiDescription.Client` package reference — it still works.
- Ensure you've called `builder.Services.AddOpenApi()` so the build-time document generation target (`GetOpenApiReference`) can produce the spec.
- Remove any residual Swashbuckle/`Swashbuckle.AspNetCore` references; they're no longer the backing engine.

---

**5. `IActionContextAccessor` as singleton → scoped**

Registering `IActionContextAccessor` as a singleton now throws. It wraps an `AsyncLocal`, so a singleton registration was always misleading; .NET 10 enforces correctness:

```csharp
// Before (.NET 9)
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IActionContextAccessor, ActionContextAccessor>();

// After (.NET 10)
builder.Services.AddHttpContextAccessor();               // if you also need IHttpContextAccessor
builder.Services.AddScoped<IActionContextAccessor, ActionContextAccessor>();
```

---

**6. `IPNetwork` type change**

The ASP.NET-specific `Microsoft.AspNetCore.HttpOverrides.IPNetwork` struct is removed. Use `System.Net.IPNetwork` (available since .NET 8):

```csharp
// Before (.NET 9)
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.HttpOverrides;
options.KnownNetworks.Add(new IPNetwork(IPAddress.Parse("10.0.0.0"), 8));

// After (.NET 10)
using System.Net;
options.KnownNetworks.Add(new IPNetwork(IPAddress.Parse("10.0.0.0"), 8));
// Same call signature — just a different using/namespace.
```

---

**7. `AddRazorRuntimeCompilation()` removed**

Runtime compilation of Razor views/pages is removed entirely. Use **Hot Reload** instead:

```bash
dotnet watch   # automatically applies Razor changes at dev time
```

Remove the `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Razor.RuntimeCompilation` package reference and the `AddRazorRuntimeCompilation()` call from your service configuration.

---

**8. Cookie auth 401 → login redirect on API endpoints**

.NET 10 changes the default cookie authentication behavior for API-style projects. Instead of returning a `302` redirect to the login page, API endpoints now return a proper `401` by default. If your code had a manual workaround, you can simplify:

```csharp
// Before (.NET 9) — manual workaround
services.ConfigureApplicationCookie(options => {
    options.Events.OnRedirectToLogin = context => {
        context.Response.StatusCode = 401;
        return Task.CompletedTask;
    };
});

// After (.NET 10) — this is now the default for endpoints
// that don't have an associated login path. Remove the
// workaround if you have one; or if you *want* the redirect,
// explicitly set options.LoginPath.
```

---

### Quick checklist

| Area | Action |
|---|---|
| Hosting | Replace `WebHostBuilder` → `WebApplication.CreateBuilder` |
| OpenAPI | `AddOpenApi()` + `MapOpenApi()`; drop `WithOpenApi()` |
| Analyzers | Remove `<IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers>` from csproj |
| NSwag | Keep `ApiDescription.Client`; drop Swashbuckle |
| DI | `IActionContextAccessor` → scoped registration |
| Networking | `using System.Net;` for `IPNetwork` |
| Razor | Remove runtime compilation; use `dotnet watch` |
| Auth | 401 now returned directly for APIs (no redirect) |
